Over the years, phosphorus from fertilizer has piled up in Lake Okeechobee. Water leaving the lake in recent years contained about 128 parts per billion and about 119 parts per billion when it reached treatment marshes that filtered the pollution, leaving it dramatically cleaner. Water in the Everglades reservoir would also be polluted and need to be cleaned before it can be pumped south. Source: South Florida Water Management District
